    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2feebd79_a1ad519b",
        "filename": "run.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 1,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-24T15:19:02Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is an example \"recipe\".  There\u0027s a lot I\u0027m not happy with.  I wanted to rewrite one of our existing recipes (infra, at least) in this framework, but I\u0027d want to reuse git.NewCheckout() for the first step(s), and that indirectly uses os.Stat().  If the git commands are being mocked out for testing, then the os calls must be also, or else we run into consistency problems (eg. file/dir not present even after git clone).  Personally, I think the only way to pull this off is to build our own wrapper of the built-in os package, and enforce usage of that everywhere.  Otherwise, we can\u0027t guarantee that something doesn\u0027t call into those functions.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 1,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "8099fde41beff266a3d35f0ce31323713173c3fd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "150df937_9496c1cc",
        "filename": "run.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 1,
      "author": {
        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-24T17:26:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Excessive use of mocks is a bad idea and doesn\u0027t really add anything to testing. For example: Recipes has 100% code coverage and mocks out everything it touches, and they land changes almost weekly that break our bots. Let\u0027s not make writing recipes that much harder for little to no gain.",
      "parentUuid": "2feebd79_a1ad519b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 1,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "8099fde41beff266a3d35f0ce31323713173c3fd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8c240236_41cedf65",
        "filename": "run.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 1,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-25T12:03:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So what\u0027s the alternative?  If we don\u0027t have wrappers around \"actions\" (eg. run a command, perform a filesystem operation, etc), how will we emit step metadata when they occur?  I thought the consensus from the brainstorming doc was that steps were important to keep and that we don\u0027t just want to replace recipes with opaque Go programs.",
      "parentUuid": "150df937_9496c1cc",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 1,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "8099fde41beff266a3d35f0ce31323713173c3fd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e45efe1c_6ed368ed",
        "filename": "run.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 1,
      "author": {
        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-25T13:47:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You can wrap actions, but a wrapper around \u0027os\u0027 is a waste of time.\nThat is, there\u0027s a big difference between wrapping \u0027os\u0027 and having steps that look like:\n\nfunc Step(c step.Context) error {\n   c.Report(\"starting git clone\")\n   if c.IsTesting {\n      return nil\n   }\n   ....\n}",
      "parentUuid": "8c240236_41cedf65",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 1,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "8099fde41beff266a3d35f0ce31323713173c3fd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0ef24eda_ed9490c8",
        "filename": "run.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 1,
      "author": {
        "id": 5015
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-25T14:42:38Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think I\u0027m getting too concerned with tracking 100% of what goes on inside the automation code. Assuming we have tests for the components which get used, we shouldn\u0027t need to see every change in behavior.  In which case there\u0027s no need to stress over getting wrappers for everything, although it\u0027d still be nice to monitor what\u0027s happening, eg. which commands we ran.",
      "parentUuid": "e45efe1c_6ed368ed",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 1,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "8099fde41beff266a3d35f0ce31323713173c3fd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "95419bd1_6bdae65d",
        "filename": "run.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 1,
      "author": {
        "id": 5205
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-09-25T15:07:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\"Assuming we have tests for the components which get used, we shouldn\u0027t need to see every change in behavior. \"\n\n+1\n\n\"it\u0027d still be nice to monitor what\u0027s happening, eg. which commands we ran.\"\n\nRight, I don\u0027t think it\u0027s possible, or even a goal, to make this system so bullet proof we never ship a broken recipe, I\u0027d rather focus our effort on making these easy to debug when we do make a mistake.",
      "parentUuid": "0ef24eda_ed9490c8",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 1,
        "startChar": 0,
